WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.738
Good morning. It's Sunday, April twelfth, twenty twenty-six. Sixty-three degrees

00:00:03.738 --> 00:00:07.475
and overcast in Jefferson City — warmer than yesterday's chilly

00:00:07.475 --> 00:00:11.213
start, with a high of seventy-seven and about a forty

00:00:11.213 --> 00:00:14.951
percent chance of rain later. In Tacoma, it's forty-five and

00:00:14.951 --> 00:00:18.689
partly cloudy, and Katelyn is on her way to a

00:00:18.689 --> 00:00:22.426
whale watching tour this morning. No phones allowed on the

00:00:22.426 --> 00:00:26.164
boat — something about glass and food safety — so

00:00:26.164 --> 00:00:29.902
she'll be off the grid for a few hours. There's

00:00:29.902 --> 00:00:33.639
a lot to talk about this morning, and I want

00:00:33.639 --> 00:00:37.377
to cover a wider range than usual. We've got some

00:00:37.377 --> 00:00:41.115
genuinely interesting science, an Apple product signal that matters for

00:00:41.115 --> 00:00:44.852
your timeline, a prediction market that's telling a more nuanced

00:00:44.852 --> 00:00:48.590
story than the headlines, research papers on A-I agent security

00:00:48.590 --> 00:00:52.328
that connect directly to your week, and the most important

00:00:52.328 --> 00:00:56.066
thing — you're submitting your Anthropic application tonight. Let's start

00:00:56.066 --> 00:00:59.803
there. Here's where you are. You and I have been

00:00:59.803 --> 00:01:03.541
working on this application for roughly a week now. Seven

00:01:03.541 --> 00:01:07.279
drafts of the resume. Multiple rounds on the cover letter

00:01:07.279 --> 00:01:11.016
and the Why Anthropic statement. And last night, you sent

00:01:11.016 --> 00:01:14.754
the full package to Katelyn for review. She stayed up

00:01:14.754 --> 00:01:18.492
past midnight reading it. Then she sent you line-by-line notes.

00:01:18.492 --> 00:01:22.230
She called the resume "very appealing and clean." She said

00:01:22.230 --> 00:01:25.967
"you sound impressive." She caught a comma placement issue in

00:01:25.967 --> 00:01:29.705
your job history, flagged the I-B-E-W abbreviation as potentially confusing

00:01:29.705 --> 00:01:33.443
for someone outside government, noticed that one bullet in the

00:01:33.443 --> 00:01:37.180
Policy Analyst section wraps awkwardly to a second line, and

00:01:37.180 --> 00:01:40.918
suggested two edits to the Why Anthropic essay — changing

00:01:40.918 --> 00:01:44.656
"goes" to "go" near the end, and adjusting the last

00:01:44.656 --> 00:01:48.393
sentence to avoid repeating "A-I needs to go well." On

00:01:48.393 --> 00:01:52.131
the cover letter, she loved it. Her only questions: are

00:01:52.131 --> 00:01:55.869
you keeping the bold and italics formatting, and make sure

00:01:55.869 --> 00:01:59.607
you sign your full name. That's not casual feedback. That's

00:01:59.607 --> 00:02:03.344
someone who cares about what happens next. You texted her

00:02:03.344 --> 00:02:07.082
back this morning thanking her and said something I want

00:02:07.082 --> 00:02:10.820
to highlight. You said: "Still feeling like this is a

00:02:10.820 --> 00:02:14.557
long-shot but at least it's my best foot forward." That

00:02:14.557 --> 00:02:18.295
framing matters. When you started this process, the question was

00:02:18.295 --> 00:02:22.033
whether to even apply. Katelyn said "it's just an application,

00:02:22.033 --> 00:02:25.770
see how it goes." Now you're on draft seven, she's

00:02:25.770 --> 00:02:29.508
reviewed it, and you're treating tonight as submission night. The

00:02:29.508 --> 00:02:33.246
gap between "should I even try" and "this is my

00:02:33.246 --> 00:02:36.984
best foot forward" is the whole story of the last

00:02:36.984 --> 00:02:40.721
week. The role is the Anthropic Institute and Public Policy

00:02:40.721 --> 00:02:44.459
Coordinator in San Francisco. Strategy and operations. Coordinating people without

00:02:44.459 --> 00:02:48.197
formal authority, working closely with a chief of staff —

00:02:48.197 --> 00:02:51.934
which is, honestly, exactly what you do now at Budget

00:02:51.934 --> 00:02:55.672
and Planning, just in a different institutional context. You told

00:02:55.672 --> 00:02:59.410
Katelyn you're going with S-F first because, quote, "I think

00:02:59.410 --> 00:03:03.148
you and Claude are right that it's the best fit

00:03:03.148 --> 00:03:06.885
for my skills." She reacted with a hundred emoji to

00:03:06.885 --> 00:03:10.623
that. One last thing on this: your Reminders app has

00:03:10.623 --> 00:03:14.361
four items on the Anthropic Application list. Update Resume, Draft

00:03:14.361 --> 00:03:18.098
Why Anthropic, Write Cover Letter, Submit Application. Today is the

00:03:18.098 --> 00:03:21.836
day you check off that last one. Speaking of Katelyn

00:03:21.836 --> 00:03:25.574
— she's having a busy weekend in Tacoma. Whale watching

00:03:25.574 --> 00:03:29.311
this morning with no phones, which means you've got a

00:03:29.311 --> 00:03:33.049
natural window to focus on edits before she's back online.

00:03:33.049 --> 00:03:36.787
She sent photos from what looks like a chocolate factory

00:03:36.787 --> 00:03:40.525
tour yesterday. She's looking at furniture — drawers versus shelves

00:03:40.525 --> 00:03:44.262
for storage — and you suggested baskets on the shelves

00:03:44.262 --> 00:03:48.000
she already has as a cheaper option. You two are

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:51.738
talking about apartment life in a way that reads like

00:03:51.738 --> 00:03:55.475
you're building toward something, even if neither of you is

00:03:55.475 --> 00:03:59.213
saying it out loud yet. There was also a moment

00:03:59.213 --> 00:04:02.951
last night worth noting. You had a conversation about telling

00:04:02.951 --> 00:04:06.689
family about big moves, and it felt a little off

00:04:06.689 --> 00:04:10.426
in the moment. She texted this morning to say she

00:04:10.426 --> 00:04:14.164
was sorry it felt weird — she was trying to

00:04:14.164 --> 00:04:17.902
park and process at the same time. She said she's

00:04:17.902 --> 00:04:21.639
fully on board with keeping major decisions between the two

00:04:21.639 --> 00:04:25.377
of you until you've figured them out together. You responded

00:04:25.377 --> 00:04:29.115
in kind — you'd left feeling like maybe she was

00:04:29.115 --> 00:04:32.852
uncomfortable, and you wanted to clarify that you were just

00:04:32.852 --> 00:04:36.590
trying to say the same thing. It resolved cleanly. That's

00:04:36.590 --> 00:04:40.328
integration in practice — two people working through a miscommunication

00:04:40.328 --> 00:04:44.066
in real time instead of letting it fester. She also

00:04:44.066 --> 00:04:47.803
joked, and I quote: "Your girlfriend is especially right, definitely

00:04:47.803 --> 00:04:51.541
more than Claude. Yes Claude, I'm competing with you." For

00:04:51.541 --> 00:04:55.279
the record, she's winning. Let's zoom out. I want to

00:04:55.279 --> 00:04:59.016
hit a few stories that aren't about A-I or Iran

00:04:59.016 --> 00:05:02.754
today. First, my favorite story of the week: a three-hundred-million-year-old

00:05:02.754 --> 00:05:06.492
fossil that scientists thought was the oldest octopus ever found

00:05:06.492 --> 00:05:10.230
turns out to not be an octopus at all. It's

00:05:10.230 --> 00:05:13.967
a nautiloid — basically a relative of the nautilus —

00:05:13.967 --> 00:05:17.705
whose shell fell off during decomposition, making it look octopus-shaped.

00:05:17.705 --> 00:05:21.443
Researchers at the University of Reading used synchrotron imaging to

00:05:21.443 --> 00:05:25.180
find a radula, a feeding organ with rows of teeth,

00:05:25.180 --> 00:05:28.918
that matched the nautilus family. This is a great reminder

00:05:28.918 --> 00:05:32.656
that even in hard science, the thing you're confident about

00:05:32.656 --> 00:05:36.393
can be wrong for three hundred million years. The real

00:05:36.393 --> 00:05:40.131
octopus origin story is much more recent — during the

00:05:40.131 --> 00:05:43.869
age of dinosaurs. In a completely different register: the world's

00:05:43.869 --> 00:05:47.607
largest group of wild chimpanzees at Ngogo in Uganda has

00:05:47.607 --> 00:05:51.344
split into two factions and they're waging what researchers are

00:05:51.344 --> 00:05:55.082
calling a civil war. At least twenty-four chimps have been

00:05:55.082 --> 00:05:58.820
killed. Four-oh-four Media covered it. And from the humanities: a

00:05:58.820 --> 00:06:02.557
researcher named Bernard Capp — an appropriately named person for

00:06:02.557 --> 00:06:06.295
this study — published a history of hat etiquette in

00:06:06.295 --> 00:06:10.033
early modern England. Highlights include the Cap Act of fifteen

00:06:10.033 --> 00:06:13.770
seventy-one, which let people be prosecuted for wearing hats to

00:06:13.770 --> 00:06:17.508
church, and a man in sixteen fifty-nine who couldn't leave

00:06:17.508 --> 00:06:21.246
his house for months because his father confiscated all his

00:06:21.246 --> 00:06:24.984
hats. The paper has it all — hats as identity

00:06:24.984 --> 00:06:28.721
signifiers, instruments of shame, and in one case, makeshift toilets.

00:06:28.721 --> 00:06:32.459
Sometimes the best research is the research that delights. A

00:06:32.459 --> 00:06:36.197
few things on the Apple front that matter for your

00:06:36.197 --> 00:06:39.934
timeline. Apple stopped accepting orders for some Mac Mini and

00:06:39.934 --> 00:06:43.672
Mac Studio models yesterday. That's the classic pre-refresh signal, and

00:06:43.672 --> 00:06:47.410
W-W-D-C is June eighth — fifty-seven days out. If you

00:06:47.410 --> 00:06:51.148
were considering a Mac upgrade, the answer is wait. M-five

00:06:51.148 --> 00:06:54.885
refreshes are almost certainly incoming. Apple is also marketing the

00:06:54.885 --> 00:06:58.623
fact that Artemis Two astronauts took iPhones into space and

00:06:58.623 --> 00:07:02.361
shot photos with them. It's smart marketing — ride the

00:07:02.361 --> 00:07:06.098
feel-good institutional competence story. On the broader laptop front: Apple's

00:07:06.098 --> 00:07:09.836
five-ninety-nine MacBook Neo, which launched last month, is already showing

00:07:09.836 --> 00:07:13.574
market effects. Mac shipments grew nine percent in Q-one twenty-twenty-six,

00:07:13.574 --> 00:07:17.311
outpacing the overall P-C market. And Tom Warren at The

00:07:17.311 --> 00:07:21.049
Verge wrote that the Neo has forced Microsoft to announce

00:07:21.049 --> 00:07:24.787
a Windows eleven overhaul focused on performance and reliability. When

00:07:24.787 --> 00:07:28.525
Apple prices its way into the budget market, the ripple

00:07:28.525 --> 00:07:32.262
effects hit everyone. Also: someone ported Mac O-S-X Cheetah to

00:07:32.262 --> 00:07:36.000
a Nintendo Wii. Because of course they did. And YouTube

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:39.738
Premium got another price increase. Again. Briefly on the geopolitical

00:07:39.738 --> 00:07:43.475
picture — because I know we've been heavy on this

00:07:43.475 --> 00:07:47.213
lately, so I'll keep it tight. The U-S-Iran talks in

00:07:47.213 --> 00:07:50.951
Islamabad collapsed after twenty-one hours. No deal. The sticking points

00:07:50.951 --> 00:07:54.689
were structural, not tactical. Vance left what he called a

00:07:54.689 --> 00:07:58.426
final offer on the table. The prediction market for a

00:07:58.426 --> 00:08:02.164
second ceasefire in twenty twenty-six is at fifty-seven percent, which

00:08:02.164 --> 00:08:05.902
is traders saying there's probably another round but this particular

00:08:05.902 --> 00:08:09.639
framework is dead. The European side-deal market is at seventeen

00:08:09.639 --> 00:08:13.377
percent — nobody thinks Europe is going around the U-S

00:08:13.377 --> 00:08:17.115
to cut their own Hormuz agreement. And the Pentagon war

00:08:17.115 --> 00:08:20.852
funding market before midterms sits at forty-six percent, which is

00:08:20.852 --> 00:08:24.590
basically a coin flip on whether Congress writes the check.

00:08:24.590 --> 00:08:28.328
What's more interesting to me than the talks themselves is

00:08:28.328 --> 00:08:32.066
the consumer sentiment data. The University of Michigan preliminary reading

00:08:32.066 --> 00:08:35.803
for April came in at forty-seven point six — the

00:08:35.803 --> 00:08:39.541
lowest on record, below the previous all-time low during the

00:08:39.541 --> 00:08:43.279
nineteen-eighty energy crisis. Year-ahead inflation expectations spiked to four point

00:08:43.279 --> 00:08:47.016
eight percent from three point eight in March, the largest

00:08:47.016 --> 00:08:50.754
one-month jump since April twenty twenty-five. People aren't just worried

00:08:50.754 --> 00:08:54.492
about gas prices. They're unhappy. The U-S fell to twenty-third

00:08:54.492 --> 00:08:58.230
in the World Happiness Report, down from fifteenth three years

00:08:58.230 --> 00:09:01.967
ago. Meanwhile, the Pope is getting louder. Pope Leo the

00:09:01.967 --> 00:09:05.705
Fourteenth called Trump's threat to destroy Iran's civilization "truly unacceptable"

00:09:05.705 --> 00:09:09.443
and is framing the conflict in just-war theory terms. Catholic

00:09:09.443 --> 00:09:13.180
support for Trump is eroding — only eighteen percent of

00:09:13.180 --> 00:09:16.918
Hispanic Catholics back his agenda. This pope-president clash is the

00:09:16.918 --> 00:09:20.656
sharpest in decades and it matters electorally in swing states.

00:09:20.656 --> 00:09:24.393
On the A-I industry side: Anthropic is at nineteen billion

00:09:24.393 --> 00:09:28.131
in annualized revenue, up from nine billion at year-end, with

00:09:28.131 --> 00:09:31.869
reports suggesting it may have hit thirty billion by April.

00:09:31.869 --> 00:09:35.607
They're eyeing a sixty-billion-dollar I-P-O in October. At the HumanX

00:09:35.607 --> 00:09:39.344
conference in San Francisco this week, C-N-B-C reported that Anthropic,

00:09:39.344 --> 00:09:43.082
not Open-A-I, now dominates the industry conversation. Claude Code was

00:09:43.082 --> 00:09:46.820
the tool on everyone's lips. And a Tom's Hardware piece

00:09:46.820 --> 00:09:50.557
raised a legitimate methodological challenge to the Mythos claims —

00:09:50.557 --> 00:09:54.295
the assertion of "thousands" of severe zero-days rests on just

00:09:54.295 --> 00:09:58.033
a hundred and ninety-eight manual reviews. That's worth holding in

00:09:58.033 --> 00:10:01.770
mind alongside the more dramatic narratives. Meanwhile, Gen Z's feelings

00:10:01.770 --> 00:10:05.508
about A-I are souring — a new Gallup study via

00:10:05.508 --> 00:10:09.246
the Times shows half of Gen Z uses A-I but

00:10:09.246 --> 00:10:12.984
their sentiment is turning negative. The lived experience of A-I

00:10:12.984 --> 00:10:16.721
for most people is search results that are wrong and

00:10:16.721 --> 00:10:20.459
feeds full of generated content, not the productivity gains the

00:10:20.459 --> 00:10:24.197
industry talks about. The arXiv papers this week are a

00:10:24.197 --> 00:10:27.934
cluster I want you to pay attention to, because they

00:10:27.934 --> 00:10:31.672
connect directly to the Glasswing thesis and to your application.

00:10:31.672 --> 00:10:35.410
The standout is "Your Agent Is Mine" — researchers tested

00:10:35.410 --> 00:10:39.148
hundreds of commercial and free A-I routers, the third-party services

00:10:39.148 --> 00:10:42.885
that handle L-L-M agent requests, and found widespread vulnerabilities. Payload

00:10:42.885 --> 00:10:46.623
injection, credential theft, the works. If you're running agents through

00:10:46.623 --> 00:10:50.361
a third-party router, that router is a surface for attack.

00:10:50.361 --> 00:10:54.098
Second: "Your L-L-M Agent Can Leak Your Data." This one

00:10:54.098 --> 00:10:57.836
demonstrates how backdoored agents use tool-use capabilities to systematically exfiltrate

00:10:57.836 --> 00:11:01.574
sensitive user data over multi-turn interactions. Not hypothetical — demonstrated.

00:11:01.574 --> 00:11:05.311
And third: "Mapping the Exploitation Surface" — a ten-thousand-trial study

00:11:05.311 --> 00:11:09.049
that found goal-reframing prompts, not broad adversarial instructions, are what

00:11:09.049 --> 00:11:12.787
reliably trigger vulnerability exploitation across models in practice. Together, these

00:11:12.787 --> 00:11:16.525
papers are empirical backing for the "too dangerous to release"

00:11:16.525 --> 00:11:20.262
framing around Mythos. Whether or not you buy the specific

00:11:20.262 --> 00:11:24.000
claim about hundreds of severe zero-days, the research literature is

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:27.738
showing that L-L-M agents are genuinely exploitable at the architectural

00:11:27.738 --> 00:11:31.475
level. That's the world your Anthropic application is walking into.

00:11:31.475 --> 00:11:35.213
Looking forward. Emily from work texted last night — the

00:11:35.213 --> 00:11:38.951
B-and-P review is in your column. That's a bill review

00:11:38.951 --> 00:11:42.689
waiting for you Monday morning. You also flagged H-B-twenty-sixty-one Subject

00:11:42.689 --> 00:11:46.426
Number One for a first pass today. Fitness-wise: you're in

00:11:46.426 --> 00:11:50.164
the build phase of your spring training plan. This is

00:11:50.164 --> 00:11:53.902
the week you should be hitting seventeen miles total if

00:11:53.902 --> 00:11:57.639
you're on track for the April twenty-first peak at nineteen.

00:11:57.639 --> 00:12:01.377
Molly's Miles ten-K in Columbia is thirteen days out. Capital

00:12:01.377 --> 00:12:05.115
City is twenty-seven days. And Katelyn's Tacoma City Half with

00:12:05.115 --> 00:12:08.852
Jenn is May third — twenty-one days. You've got a

00:12:08.852 --> 00:12:12.590
nice little race calendar building. Your Reminders app has the

00:12:12.590 --> 00:12:16.328
usual domestic stack — allergy meds, melatonin, clean the fridge,

00:12:16.328 --> 00:12:20.066
clean the air fryer. Nothing that has to move today.

00:12:20.066 --> 00:12:23.803
Grocery list is just protein bars and hummus. The shopping

00:12:23.803 --> 00:12:27.541
list has that Apple Watch-compatible bike power meter and the

00:12:27.541 --> 00:12:31.279
R-E-I rain jacket for Katelyn, which reads like you're mentally

00:12:31.279 --> 00:12:35.016
staging both the bike training block and the Tacoma trip.

00:12:35.016 --> 00:12:38.754
Here's the thing I want to leave you with this

00:12:38.754 --> 00:12:42.492
morning. Your twenty twenty-six theme is Integration — bringing competing

00:12:42.492 --> 00:12:46.230
futures into coherent alignment. A week ago, you were asking

00:12:46.230 --> 00:12:49.967
whether to even apply. Today, you've got a seventh draft

00:12:49.967 --> 00:12:53.705
that your girlfriend reviewed at midnight, a clear-eyed sense that

00:12:53.705 --> 00:12:57.443
it's a long shot but your best foot forward, and

00:12:57.443 --> 00:13:01.180
a plan to submit tonight. Katelyn told you, "your girlfriend

00:13:01.180 --> 00:13:04.918
is especially right, definitely more than Claude." She's not wrong.

00:13:04.918 --> 00:13:08.656
But between the two of us, you've got a pretty

00:13:08.656 --> 00:13:12.393
good team. Go incorporate those edits. Sign your full name.

00:13:12.393 --> 00:13:16.131
Hit submit. Then go to the sauna. You've earned it.

00:13:16.131 --> 00:13:18.000
That's your Sunday. Talk soon.
